Box Plot

  • The box plot provides information about the center, spread, symmetry or skewness, and possible outliers.

  • The box plot displays the five-number summary for a quantitative variable.

  • By definition, the five-number summary consists of the minimum, first quartile (Q1), median, third quartile (Q3), and the maximum.

  • In the coffee concentration data, the five-number summary are: 55, 85, 122.5, 167.5, 195

  • Outliers in the box plot are represented with “dots” beyond the box plots’ whiskers.

Outliers

  • By definition, any observation is considered to be an outlier if it is more than 1.5 times the IQR away from the nearest quartile (the nearest end of the box).

  • In other words: a data value is an outlier if it is “greater than” Q3 + 1.5(IQR) or “less than” Q1 - 1.5(IQR).

  • In the coffee concentration data, the lower fence is 85 - 1.5(82.5) = -38.75. On the other hand, the upper fence is 167.5 + 1.5(82.5) = 291.25

  • Since no data value is less than -38.75 or greater than 219.25, the coffee concentration data do not have “outliers”.

  • Outliers are “rare” observations in your data.

  • If you detect outliers, it is recommended to inspect them as possible data entry or measurement errors. If they are correct data, keep them for your analysis.

The following data contains the ages at which Oscar winning actresses won their awards (“Ages of Oscar-Winning Best Actors and Actresses”, Richard Brown and Gretchen Davis, Mathematics Teacher magazine): 50, 30, 61, 44, 33, 60, 35, 41, 34, 80, 31, 24, 26, 35, 60, 28, 41, 37, 41, 42, 31, 21, 37, 27, 61, 26, 39, 38, 34, 34, 49, 34, 26, 33, 35, 25, 74, 26, 33. Determine whether the distribution is symmetric or skewed, the appropriate typical value and measure of variability, identify possible outliers and display these data in a box plot.

Numerical summary of Age

   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  21.00   30.00   35.00   38.87   42.00   80.00

  • Data distribution is skewed to the right

  • The typical value is the median = 35 and the measure of the spread is IQR = 12

  • Lower fence = Q1 - (1.5)IQR = 30 - (1.5)(12) = 12

  • Upper fence = Q3 + (1.5)IQR = 42 + (1.5)(12) = 60

  • The values of the outliers are 60, 61, 74 and 80 are outliers.

  • Note: The boxplot created with statistical software did not extend the upper fence to 60. It stopped at 50, the observation value before 60 on the data set.

Measures of Relative Standing (Z score)

  • The Z-Score corresponding to a particular value, X, with mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\) is:

  • Z = \(\frac{X - \mu}{\sigma}\)

  • Interpretation: The Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations an observation X is to the mean \(\mu\).

  • A positive Z-score indicates that the observation is above the mean. A negative sign suggests the observation is below the mean.

  • Since the Z-score measures the relative standing of X with respect the mean, it is possible to compare observations with different distributions (shape of the histogram).

The first Stats exam had a mean of 65 and standard deviation of 10 points; the second exam had a mean of 80 and a standard deviation of 5 points. Derrick scored an 80 on both tests. Julie scored a 70 on the first test and a 90 on the second. They both totaled 160 points on the two exams, but Julie claims that her total is better. Explain. \(\phantom{DI3-148-15 Combining Test Scores (ActivStats):}\)

  • Exam 1 and Exam 2 have different scores distributions. Therefore, it is not possible to make a comparison.

  • The solution is to “standardize” the test scores with respect the average for each distribution. Z = \(\frac{X - \mu}{\sigma}\)

  • Derrick: \(Z_1\) = \(\frac{80 - 65}{10}\) = 1.5, and \(Z_2\) = \(\frac{80 - 80}{5}\) = 0

  • Derrick (Total Z-score) = 1.5 + 0 = 1.5

  • Julie: \(Z_1\) = \(\frac{70 - 65}{10}\) = 0.5, and \(Z_2\) = \(\frac{90 - 80}{5}\) = 2

  • Julie (Total Z-score) = 0.5 + 2 = 2.5

  • In overall, Julie has a better score, 2.5.

The Empirical Rule (68-95-99.7%)

If a distribution is “roughly” bell shaped, then:

  • Approximately 68% of the data will lie within 1 standard deviation to the mean. \((\mu - \sigma)\) and \((\mu + \sigma)\)

  • Approximately 95% of the data will lie within 2 standard deviation to the mean. \((\mu - 2\sigma)\) and \((\mu + 2\sigma)\)

  • Approximately 99.7% of the data will lie within 3 standard deviation to the mean. \((\mu - 3\sigma)\) and \((\mu + 3\sigma)\)

  • The empirical rule is an “approximation” to the exact proportion of the area (or percentage) corresponding to the normal density curve.

  • The empirical rule deals ONLY with areas 1, 2, or 3 standard deviations within the mean. For standard deviations beyond 3, the area within is approximately ONE.

Empirical Rule, 68-95-99.7, Summary

Std. Dev WITHIN \(\mu\) Central area Left tail area Right Tail area
1 68% 16% 16%
2 95% 2.5% 2.5%
3 99.7% 0.15% 0.15%

Exercise: One measure of intelligence is the Stanford-Binet Intelligence Quotient (IQ). IQ scores have a bell-shaped distribution with mean of 100 and standard deviation of 15. Using the Empirical Rule answer the following questions: \(\phantom{Sullivan, ex29, p.143}\)

a) What percentage of people has an IQ score between 70 and 130?

  • Since the distribution is bell-shaped, use the “empirical rule”.

  • Step 1: Sketch the distribution with the area between 70 and 130.

  • Step 2: Identify how many standard deviations is 70 and 130 to the mean, 100.

  • Step 3: Use the empirical rule for the corresponding distances found in step 2.

  • Since 70 and 130 are 2 standard deviations to the mean, use the 95% rule.

  • Therefore, we can say that 95% of people have IQ between 70 and 130.

b) What percentage of people has an IQ score less than 70 or greater than 130?

  • The areas for “less than 70” and “greater than 130” refer to the left and right tails respectively.

  • Since 70 and 130 are within two standard deviations, we use the 95% rule.

  • Therefore, the total area of the tails for two standard deviations is 5%

  • About 5% of the people have IQ score less than 70 or greater than 130.

c) What percentage of people has an IQ score between 85 and 145?

  • Identify that 85 is “one” standard deviation below the mean, and 145 is “three” standard deviations above the mean.

  • These z-scores imply the use of the 68% and 99.7% rule; however, we need to consider only half of each percent.

  • One standard deviation below the mean is just 34% (lower half of 68% for within) and three standard deviations above the mean is just 49.85% (upper half of 99.7% for within)

  • The total area between 85 and 145 is 34% + 49.85% = 83.85%

Empirical Rule (combining areas)

  • The graph below shows that the area for values between two standard deviations below the mean, z = -2, and one standard deviation above the mean, z = 1, is 47.5 + 34 = 81.5%. The red area is the lower half of 95% and the blue area is the upper half of 68%.

  • This graph displays the area for values less than one standard deviations below the mean, 16%, and those between the mean and two standard deviations above the mean, 47.5%.

Chebyshev’s Rule

  • Consider any number k, where k > 1.

  • The percentage of observations that are within k standard deviations to the mean is at least 100(1 - \(\frac{1}{k^2}\))%

  • When k=2, 1 - \(\frac{1}{2^2}\) = 0.75. At least 75% of the observations is within two standard deviations to the mean.

  • When k=3, 1 - \(\frac{1}{3^2}\) = 0.89. At least 89% of the observations is within three standard deviations to the mean.

  • When k=4, 1 - \(\frac{1}{4^2}\) = 0.94. At least 94% of the observations is within four standard deviations to the mean.

Mobile homes are tightly constructed for energy conservation. This can lead to a buildup of indoor pollutants. The paper “a Survey of nitrogen Dioxide levels inside mobile Homes” (Journal of the Air Pollution Control Association [1988]: 647–651) discussed various aspects of NO2 concentration in these structures.

a) In one sample of mobile homes in the Los Angeles area, the mean NO2 concentration in kitchens during the summer was 36.92 ppb, and the standard deviation was 11.34. Making no assumptions about the shape of the NO2 distribution, what can be said about the percentage of observations between 14.24 and 59.60? \(\phantom{Peck5, ex4.41, p.185}\)

  • Use Chevyshev’s rule when there is no assumption about the data distribution.

  • Compute the number of standard deviations, k, 14.24 and 59.60 are to the mean.

  • \(\frac{14.24 - 36.92}{11.34}\) = -2, \(\frac{59.60 - 36.92}{11.34}\) = 2. Take k = 2

  • Compute the percentage: \((1 - \frac{1}{k^2})\)x100 = \((1 - \frac{1}{2^2})\)x100 = 75%

  • AT LEAST 75% of the observations are between 14.24 and 59.60ppb.

b) Inside what interval is it guaranteed that at least 89% of the concentration observations will lie?

  • The “at least 89%” implies that k=3. (Hint: 1 - \(\frac{1}{k^2}\) = 0.89)

  • Lower bound of interval: 36.92 - (3)(11.34) = 2.9

  • Upper bound of interval: 36.92 + (3)(11.34) = 70.94

  • At least 89% of the concentration observations will lie between 2.9 and 70.94 ppb.

c) In a sample of non–Los Angeles mobile homes, the average kitchen NO2 concentration during the winter was 24.76 ppb, and the standard deviation was 17.20. Do these values suggest that the histogram of sample observations did not closely resemble a normal curve?

  • Hint: What is \(\bar{X}\) - 2s?

  • 24.76 - (2)(17.20) = -9.64

  • A negative concentration value suggests that the histogram did not resemble a normal curve.

The average reading speed of students completing a speed-reading course is 450 words per minute (wpm). If the standard deviation is 70 wpm, find the z score associated with 320 wpm. \(\phantom{Peck5, ex4.50, p.186}\)

  • Z = \(\frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}\)

  • Z = \(\frac{320 - 450}{70}\)

  • Z = -1.85

An advertisement for the “30-inch wonder” that appeared in the September 1983 issue of the journal Packaging claimed that the 30-inch Wonder weighs cases and bags up to 110 pounds and provides accuracy to within 0.25 ounce. Suppose that a 50-ounce weight was repeatedly weighed on this scale and the weight readings recorded. The mean value was 49.5 ounces, and the standard deviation was 0.1. What can be said about the percentage of the time that the scale actually showed a weight that was within 0.25 ounce of the true value of 50 ounces? \(\phantom{Peck5, ex4.47, p.186}\)

  • We require the proportion of observations between 49.75 and 50.25.

  • Do you know nothing about the distribution of weight readings? If no, then use the Chevyshev’s rule

  • Z = \(\frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}\) = \(\frac{49.75 - 49.5}{0.1}\) = 2.5

  • Chebyshev’s Rule tells us that at least \(100(1 - \frac{1}{2.5^2})\) = 84% of observations lie within 2.5 standard deviations to the mean.

  • Therefore, the best conclusion we can reach is that at most 16% of weight readings will be between 49.75 and 50.25.
